        <para>The Tamboti metadata records follow the <ulink url="http://www.loc.gov/standards/mods/" target="_blank">MODS</ulink> standard for bibliographical
            description curated by the US Library of Congress. "MODS" is short for "Metadata Object Description Schema." </para>
        <para>The MODS standard allows you to catalogue source material such as
            books, articles, web sites, photos, videos, maps, computer files etc. 
            You can catalogue in great detail, but also in a simple manner. 
            You can relate entries, for example, link an entry for a book to that of a movie.
            There is also an annotate function, which enables you to insert comments about a record. </para>
        <para>The MODS format is related to the MARC format, which is used by most larger libraries, for example, national libraries or university libraries. 
            MODS is widely used as an exchange format, and when resources from different libraries are
            aggregated. 
            <!--An example of a large-scale aggregation project using MODS is <ulink url="http://www.americanhistoryonline.org/" target="_blank">American History
                Online</ulink>. -->
            MODS-using sites similar to Tamboti are 
            <ulink url="http://academiccommons.columbia.edu/" target="_blank">Columbia University Academic Commons</ulink>
            and
            <ulink url="http://cdi.uvm.edu/" target="_blank">The University of Vermont Libraries' Center for Digital Initiatives</ulink>.</para>
        <!--<para>MODS is presently used as a cataloguing format primarily for "untraditional" library resources 
            such as images and web pages, but is slowly gaining ground as a format for traditional library resources as well. 
            MARC records can be converted to and from MODS records with little or no data loss.</para>-->
